## Chapter One: The Flawed Human Brain

### Humans should be great traders, but...

- Human brains possess astonishing complexity, yet are fundamentally flawed when making financial decisions
- Despite superior pattern recognition abilities, simple systematic rules often outperform human discretionary trading
- Author's own Barclays trade demonstrated this: brilliant analysis that would be impossible to replicate systematically, but a simple rule would have been more profitable
- **Cognitive biases** result in irrational behavior that overwhelms any natural advantages humans should have over simple decision-making rules

### The death of rational economic man

- Classical finance (1950s) assumed purely rational actors leading to perfectly efficient markets
- Anomalies were initially dismissed as statistically insignificant or explainable through risk factors
- No alternative model could match the self-consistency and elegance of the **efficient markets hypothesis**
- From 1980s onward, psychologists penetrated the field, finding the economist's framework of pure rationality highly amusing
- Key insight: our brains carry **baggage from the distant past** — hardwired for survival in hostile environments where quick thinking beat slow thoughtful consideration
- Deep-rooted instincts make it extremely difficult to behave rationally as classical finance expects
- This created **behavioural finance** with its unifying model: **prospect theory**

### Why we run losses and stop out profits

- **Prospect theory** explains investor mistakes when confronting certain trading decisions
- Most people show greatest reluctance to take losses, described as **"get-evenitis"** by **Hersh Shefrin**
- Taking losses is psychologically painful — we avoid crystallizing the feeling of losing money and are reluctant to admit initial purchase mistakes
- Conversely, when positions rise in value we eagerly take profits and sell quickly (as author did with BP in 2004)
- Main motivation: minimize regret by getting confirmation our initial buy decision was correct as quickly as possible
- Both effects contradict classical financial theory — actions and risk preferences should be unrelated to whether paper profits or losses have been made
- In rational theory: we want *more* risks in losing positions to get even, but want *less* risk when winning
- Unfortunately reality is opposite: taking small profits and letting losses run is almost always a bad idea

> "Unfortunately taking small profits and letting losses run is almost always a bad idea."

- Author back-tested a **trading system** mimicking early profit taking: someone taking profits on small rises but allowing losses to grow larger before cutting — an "early profit taker"
- Example: 2011 US treasury futures during sovereign debt downgrade crisis — sells short on small profit in early June, then misses the subsequent major rally
- Compared to opposite strategy ("early loss taker") on 31 futures contracts: early loss taker beat early profit taker in 27 of them
- Tests across wide variety of **asset classes** confirm: early profit taker rule (mimicking natural instincts) does worse than rule which does the opposite

### Gamblers anonymous

- Some relatives equate trading to high stakes gambling — attitude author usually dismisses, but may contain truth
- Certain types of gambling are more addictive due to factors reinforcing brain stimulation during play:
  - Illusion of control (encourages perception of skill — lottery players prefer to pick their own numbers)
  - Apparent near misses and frequent chances of *almost* winning the biggest prize
  - Lower value prizes received alongside jackpots (especially potent in lotteries and slot machines)
  - Rapid and continuous flow providing constant stimulation
- Buying a lottery ticket is not as addictive as instant lottery or scratch card where result is known immediately
- Illusion of control is almost absent when investing systematically — one reason many find it difficult to use this method
- Near miss and rapidity factors clearly more likely associated with very frequent **day trading**
- Extremely difficult to make profits when day trading quickly — only small percentage of day traders manage to cover costs and make both reasonable income and decent return on capital
- Many amateurs feel compelled to try, and continue trying despite the odds
- Their frantic churning of trades is not so very different from the addict spending hours in front of a slot machine

> "Their frantic churning of trades is not so very different from the addict spending hours in front of a slot machine."

- This brain deficiency leads to financial decisions that aren't just poor, but potentially life destroying

### Simple trading rules

- Given flaws in human brain which seriously affect decision-making, solution: use systematic **trading rules** to make decisions
- These help mitigate our serious flaws, but also allow us to exploit weaknesses that other human traders still have
- Their **cognitive biases** result in behavioural anomalies in the market
- Early loss taker rule mentioned above isn't just correcting our human instinct to run losses — it earns extra returns when other people persist in doing the opposite
- Author finds it reassuring to have explanations based on cognitive biases for why certain trading rules are consistently profitable
- Gives confidence that what he's seeing isn't just statistical blip in **back-test**
- Means relevant rules should continue to work unless human behaviour changes radically
- This theme returns in chapter three, "Systematic Trading Rules"

### Sticking to the plan

- No point running systematic trading strategy unless you can stick to it
- Suppose you make a New Year's resolution to follow early loss taker rule — like most such resolutions it will prove hard to keep
- When long position in gold futures hits 5 cent stop loss set by early loss taker rule, you'll probably start making excuses:
  - "The fundamentals are good. They haven't changed. I will just hold on a bit longer. Just this once. If it goes down 10 cents — which it won't — then I will definitely sell."
- You might not even close at 10 cent loss, kicking yourself for not selling earlier, and continue to hang on for rebound that never comes until pain is unbearable and you close out
- Small profit would also prove irresistible, with own litany of excuses why you should take it rather than wait for stop loss to be hit once
- Author calls this process of interference **meddling**
- Meddling is due to biggest **cognitive bias** of all: **overconfidence**
- We think we are cleverer than the trading system and we are
- We think we know more than the trading system and we do
- The system focuses on narrow set of quantifiable inputs, whilst we can analyze many kinds of complex information
- We think being cleverer and knowing more implies we will make better decisions — but usually don't, thanks to cognitive biases

### Commitment mechanisms

- To stop meddling with trading systems requires what economists call a **commitment mechanism**
- Idea is several thousand years old
- Earliest appearance: story of **Odysseus** — mythical Greek wanted to hear songs of Sirens without endangering himself or vessel
- So he ordered crew to stuff their ears with beeswax, tie him to mast and dutifully ignore his inevitable cries to steer ship on to rocks
- Modern example given in **Victor Niederhoffer's** book *Education of a Speculator*
- At high point in story hedge fund manager Victor has large long position in silver futures
- Author joins him in early 1980 when Hunt brothers (who had been squeezing market upwards) are about to capitulate, causing price to drop
- Victor decided to set up loss limit of 50% of winnings
- Model story on this point is Odysseus — Victor locked himself inside racquetball court instead of tying to ship's mast
- Issued instructions to assistant and future wife, **Susan**:

> "'Do not listen to my entreaties if I wish to double further. If the losses reach 50% of the winnings, reduce my positions by one-half. If I beg to be released, sell everything out.'..."

- Some rumors about liquidation by Hunts hit the fan — Victor immediately placed call to Susan: "Untie me. Disregard everything I said before"
- **Susan** closed entire position and Victor lived to fight another day
- But how can we ensure we stick to strategies without use of ropes or future wives?

### Trading systems must be objective

- To be committed you must have an **objective** trading system
- Many systems aren't objective and require some discretion to apply
- Highly subjective rule would be something like "Sell for small losses, but don't sell when I'm sure about making positioning"
- Similar in spirit to early loss taker rule defined earlier, but much too vague
- At first sign of loss likely you'll start to redefine what constitutes 'small' to justify not selling
- So-called 'rules' in many systems are ill defined, but many have 'rules' in them which allow for significant degree of subjective interpretation
- **Technical analysts** rarely agree on which patterns exist in particular chart, and what should be done with them
- Creating purely objective system is powerful commitment mechanism
- If you have subjective system and your instinct goes against it, then you'll soon be bending the rules
- But if everything is clearly defined it creates a line in the sand beyond which any deviation is obvious
- Cannot fool yourself that you are following a system if you blatantly ignore objective rules

### Automation — the use of dogs in finance and engineering

- Furthermore we can only produce **back-tests** for purely objective systems
- Another advantage of objective systems: they can be automated, and automation is good commitment mechanism
- Can't automate subjective systems because computers eyeball trend lines on charts
- Cannot make firm statements like "Buy if the 20 day moving average is above the 40 day"
- Cannot interpret commandments like "Sell once the pattern is triggered unless there is a firm sign of bullish volume without a clear indication of bullish volume"
- So objective system is one which computer *can* run — but does not mean computer *must* run it
- Can run many trading strategies using pencil and paper, or relatively simple spreadsheets, to calculate trades which you then execute manually
- Certain kinds of strategies involving complex rules, faster trading frequencies or trading in large numbers of **instruments** would be very time-consuming, or impossible, to run without automation
- But for simpler systems automation isn't necessary
- Full automation is also problematic for **discretionary traders**, although they could automate position and risk management **framework** once they've made their trading decisions manually
- Furthermore automation doesn't stop meddling
- Firstly, consider degree of automation: having system which requires human to do actual execution of automatically generated trades is still prone to meddling
- If process is completely automated from end to end then interference is harder
- Old joke: best systematic trading setup consists of computer, man and dog
- Computer runs fully automated strategy, man feeds dog, and dog bites man if he touches computer
- Secondly, any good automated software would have ways to override it in emergency
- If you desperately want to meddle then there will be frequent 'emergencies'
- Automation is of little help unless you have faith in your trading rules
- System which is fully automated but not completely trusted is potentially lethal
- Any sane person would be tempted to shut it down at first sign of trouble
- So automation aids commitment, but it must be done with well designed system in which you have full confidence

### Good system design

- What is well designed system? How make something which you can trust, commit to and won't meddle with, regardless of whether it is automated or not?
- Much easier to trust system which is **objective** — firstly, because transparent: you know given some particular data exactly what positions should be
- Secondly, you can **back-test** an objective system over history
- Will give indication of what past behaviour was, and how it should behave in future
- For example suppose system typically lost around 5% on one of every ten trading days in simulated past of your back-test
- You shouldn't worry if in real trading you lose 5% every couple of weeks
- As well as requiring systems to be objective, author also prefers those that are relatively simple, transparent and based on underlying ideas which can be explained
- Such as previous hypothesis that prospect theory explains success of early loss taking rule
- Transparency is important for gaining trust in trading systems, just as it is in politics
- In next chapter author will explain in more detail why he prefers systems whose performance and behaviour can be explained

### Over-fitting

- In addition to positive attributes there are also three significant pitfalls to avoid when designing trading systems: **over-fitting**, **overtrading** and **over-betting**
- New trading system does not arrive out of ether — has to be designed and developed by actual, probably overconfident, person
- All too easy for that person to make design mistakes due to same **cognitive biases** they are trying to escape from by trading systematically
- **Narrative fallacy**: our brains are great at seeing patterns where there are none
- When people create trading rules there is often a **fitting** process during which best rules are selected by looking at **back-test** results
- If we're not careful the rules selected will fit data too well
- Will be highly tuned to one set of market conditions and perform worse in actual trading than back-test rule would
- System will be **over-fitted**
- Narrative fallacy means we have tendency to see more predictability in historic asset prices than really existed
- So we're naturally drawn to over-fitted trading rules
- Returns to this topic in chapter three, "Fitting"
- Second bias, perhaps most serious of all: overconfidence
- Manifests itself in lack of diversification
- Surveys of individual portfolios find that most amateur investors have relatively few securities in their portfolio, with bias towards their home country, and also lack diversification across **asset classes**
- You might think that experts, with access to sophisticated quantitative tools, wouldn't make these mistakes — unfortunately they often do
- Happens when they don't consider the considerable uncertainty in expected asset returns
- Most commonly used optimisation models assume they know pattern of returns precisely
- Small changes to model inputs will produce extreme portfolios with all their eggs in one or two baskets
- Result can be just as bad or worse than portfolios of mere amateurs
- In practice many experts fiddle with raw output of optimisations until they end up reflecting their own expectations of what result should have been
- Author will discuss this further in chapter four, "Portfolio Allocation"

### Overtrading

- People are highly overconfident about their own abilities relative to others
- This is another **cognitive bias**: illusory superiority
- For example nearly all drivers consider themselves above average — theoretical impossibility and also highly unlikely given number of deaths annually from road accidents
- Both amateur investors and professional managers have tendency to trade too frequently
- There are extra costs involved in trading more often
- Overtrading suggests overconfidence in your own relative ability to overcome higher hurdle of bigger costs
- As author pointed out above, frequent trading can also be addictive and lead to behaviour which is indistinguishable from gambling
- When designing trading systems if you **over-fit** you will end up with systems that perform unrealistically well in **back-tests**, and wrongly assume that returns will easily be high enough to overcome trading costs

### Over betting

- It will be extremely difficult to refrain from meddling if you're worried about wiping out your capital
- Take system author mentioned above: system with one-in-ten chance of 5% daily loss
- If that was ten times **leveraged** you would have 10% chance of losing *half* your capital on any given day
- Most sane people would panic after losing 50% on one day, and start meddling like crazy
- Unfortunately over betting is endemic amongst amateur investors with easy access to leverage through derivatives like spread bets
- If your confidence is unbounded you can bet the maximum that your broker allows you to
- Potentially this could be ten-fold leverage on individual equity bet, equating to annual **standard deviation** of returns of around 200%
- This is nuts

### Standard deviation concept

- **Standard deviation** is measure of how dispersed some data is around its average — it's a measure of risk
- Precise formula is in glossary, but in most cases you'll use spreadsheet formula or software to calculate it
- Standard deviations often used to describe dispersion of returns of an asset, or profits from trading system
- Author uses term **volatility** as shorthand for standard deviation of returns
- One unit of standard deviation is also sometimes called a **sigma**
- In this book we'll usually be dealing with daily returns and using daily volatilities, but it's often useful to think about annualised standard deviation — how much deviation we expect to see over a year
- Standard deviation doesn't increase linearly, but with square root of time
- Over roughly 256 business days in a year you'd expect annual standard deviation to be larger by square root of 256, or 16
- So you multiply daily standard deviations by 16 to get annualised version, or divide by 16 to go from annualised to daily
- In contrast to go from *average* daily returns to annualised average returns you just multiply by number of days in a year, or 256
- Then to go from annualised to daily you divide by 256
- Equities have annualised standard deviation of about 20% a year
- Bonds tend to be safer, depending on their maturity
- Typical two year bond has annualised sigma of around 1.5% a year, and ten year bond would be more like 8%

### Gaussian normal distribution

- We often assume our returns have particular type of **distribution**
- A distribution is just a way of describing the pattern of your data
- Common distribution author uses is **Gaussian normal distribution**
- If returns are Gaussian normal, then mean and standard deviation alone are sufficient to say how likely certain returns will be
- If your daily returns are Gaussian normal then you will see movements one sigma or less around the average two-thirds of the time, and returns two sigma or less about 95% of the time
- In 2.5% of days you'd see a change more than two sigma above the average
- You'd also see a return which is two sigma worse than the average 2.5% of the time
- The Gaussian normal distribution is symmetric
- Let's consider 200% annualised standard deviation mentioned above
- 200% a year translates into 12.5% a day if you divide by square root of time, 16
- For example daily even if you're making an optimistic 200% a year, after you've divided by 256 you earn just 0.8% per day
- A plus one sigma return would be 12.5% above the average of 0.8%, or 13.3%
- A one sigma loss would be 12.5% below the average, or -11.7%
- If daily returns are Gaussian normal: you'd see returns between -11.7% and +13.3% a day around 68% of the time
- Between -24.2% and +25.8% a day 95% of the time
- Around 2.5% of the time you'd see losses of more than 24.2% a day
- That's quite a hefty daily loss which you'd get every couple of months
- As figure 4 shows about once every three years you'd lose three sigma or 37.2% in one day
- Scarily that's probably still optimistic because normal distribution tends to underestimate chance of really bad returns
- According to normal distribution we should get daily falls of more than 4 sigma about once a century
- But from 1914 to 2014 the US Dow Jones index fell by more than 4 sigma around 30 times
- You or your investors need to be comfortable with the losses you're likely to make
- Size of your positions must reflect the amount of risk you can handle
- Author will explain this in more detail in chapter six, "Volatility Targeting"

