## Appendix B: Trading Rules

### The A and B System: Early Profit Taker and Early Loss Taker

- Two simple trading rules used throughout the book as examples: **early profit taker** and **early loss taker**
- Both are variations of the **'A and B' system** with reversed parameters
- Profit taker: A = 5, B = 20 (take profits quickly, let losses run)
- Loss taker: A = 20, B = 5 (take losses quickly, let profits run)
- Author does NOT recommend using A and B system for actual trading — included for specification clarity

#### Specification of A and B System

- **Standard position size**: $100,000 divided by instrument value volatility, measured in same currency
- **Initial position**: Go long one standard position size
- **Deviation**: One daily standard deviation of returns, measured at last entry point (volatility in price points, not percentage)
- **Profit target when long**: If price rises by more than A deviations from last entry, sell out and go short one standard position (reverse)
- **Trailing stop loss when long**: If price falls by more than B deviations from its high since entry, sell and go short one standard position
- **On reversal**: Re-measure deviation level to set new stop loss and profit targets, determine new standard position size
- **Profit target when short**: Generate profit when price falls by more than A deviations from last entry; reverse to long
- **Stop loss when short**: Generate stop loss when price rises by more than B deviations from its low; reverse to long

#### Characteristics of A and B Parameters

- **If A is larger than B** (early loss taker): System hits stop losses frequently, but exploits large trends when they occur. Profitable if prices remain range bound
- **If B is larger than A** (early profit taker): System takes profits frequently but suffers losses on large adverse movements. Profitable if prices remain range bound
- **Larger values of B**: Slower trends become more profitable than faster ones
- **Smaller values of B**: System exploits faster trends better

> "Notice that this is a complete trading system, not just a trading rule, since it tells you exactly what size positions to take."

- The system does position sizing correctly for an arbitrary **volatility target** on a single instrument
- The stop loss rule for **semi-automatic traders** (part four) is based on the stop loss component of the A and B system

### The Exponentially Weighted Moving Average Crossover (EWMAC) Rule

- Trading rule briefly introduced in chapter seven
- Forecast is the difference (**crossover**) between two **exponentially weighted moving averages (EWMA)** — one fast, one slow
- Difference is standardized by recent **standard deviation** of prices
- **Forecast scalar** applied to ensure average absolute value of 10 for forecasts

#### EWMAC with Daily Prices

- Assumes working with daily prices, no weekends in price series
- Possible to work with intra-day prices but slightly more involved

#### Look-back Windows, Fast and Slow

- To pick up trends over different time periods, need EWMAC **variations** with different horizons
- Each variation specifies two look-back windows in days: shorter for fast EWMA (L_fast), larger for slow EWMA (L_slow)
- L_slow should be larger than 1, or you'll only have one price in average
- Author uses these pairs of look-back values: 2/8, 4/16, 8/32, 16/64, 32/128, 64/256

#### Decay Parameters

- EWMA formula uses **decay parameter A**, between 0 and 1
- A = 2 ÷ (L+1) where L is the look-back window
- So A_fast and A_slow values calculated from L_fast and L_slow
- Short look-back and high A value: more weight to recent prices, EWMA adjusts faster
- Author uses look-back window to calculate decay rather than specifying decay directly — more natural to think in terms of windows
- Formulation comes from Python language's 'Pandas' package specification for EWMA, which uses term 'span' rather than look-back window

#### EWMA Formula

If P_t is most recent price of instrument, then EWMA is:

(A × P_t) + (A × (1-A) × P_(t-1)) + (A × (1-A)² × P_(t-2)) + (A × (1-A)³ × P_(t-3))...

Can also calculate recursively: if yesterday's EWMA is E_(t-1), then today's EWMA is:

(A × P_t) + (E_(t-1) × (1-A))

- If A = 1, using only current price in EWMA — hence why I require L to be 2 or more

#### Slow and Fast EWMA

- **Slow EWMA** E_slow: EWMA using A_slow based on price history
- **Fast EWMA** E_fast: EWMA using A_fast based on price history

#### Raw EWMA Crossover

- E_fast minus E_slow is the raw EWMA crossover
- If positive: recent price uptrend
- If negative: prices trending down
- Since both EWMAs are measurements of price, crossover tells you by how much prices have changed recently

#### Standard Deviation Adjustment

- Standard deviation of returns in price points, NOT percentage points
- Volatility in price points equals percentage point volatility (**price volatility** as defined in chapter ten, "Position sizing") multiplied by current price

#### Forecast Scalar

- Applied to raw EWMA crossover
- Ensures forecasts have appropriate average absolute value
- Recommended value: 10
- See page 297 for more on forecast scalars

### Further Trading Rule Details

These pages contain the complete technical specification for the **EWMAC rule**, the most commonly referenced trading rule throughout the book. The appendix provides the mathematical formulas and parameter choices needed to implement the rule precisely, moving beyond the conceptual introduction given earlier in chapter seven.


<!-- pp. 301-320 -->

## Appendix B: Trading Rules (continued)

### Volatility Adjusted EWMA Crossover
- Divide raw EWMA crossover by standard deviation of daily price changes (in price points, not percentage)
- Requires return standard deviation adjustment as discussed in chapter 7

### Forecast Scalar
- Depends on look-back window (see Table 49)
- Forecast = forecast scalar × volatility adjusted EWMA crossover
- Should have average absolute value around 10

### Capped Forecast
- Forecast with values capped at +20 and -20

### Ratio of Fast and Slow Look-Backs
- **Fixed ratio of 4:1** selected to reduce parameter space
- Author tested artificial data with various lengths plus noise element
- Little difference in performance between ratios of 2 and 6
- Subsequent real data test confirmed 4:1 was reasonable
- Reduces possible look-backs to: 2:8, 3:12, 4:16, 5:20, etc.

### Which Pairs of Look-Backs to Use
- Different pairs capture different length trends
- Since unknown which trends will occur, use reasonable number of pairs
- Recommended: 2:8, 4:16, 8:32... gives enough coverage
- **Adjacent look-backs have correlation of 0.90** (Table 57, Appendix C, page 295)
- Intervening values would exceed 0.95 correlation cutoff from chapter 6 'Forecasts'
- Beyond 64:256 pair, turnover becomes excessive and **law of active management** suggests poor performance
- Not worth adding more pairs beyond this point

### Which Forecast Scalars to Use
- Author uses technique from Appendix D (page 297) with data from large futures markets
- Not focused on performance to avoid **over-fitting**
- Table 49 shows forecast scalars for different EWMAC pairs:
  - EWMAC 2,8: 10.6
  - EWMAC 4,16: 7.5
  - EWMAC 8,32: 5.3
  - EWMAC 16,64: 3.75
  - EWMAC 32,128: 2.65
  - EWMAC 64,256: 1.87

## The Carry Trading Rule

### Introduction
- **Carry rule** calculates annualized **volatility standardized** expected return
- Assumes nothing happens to prices
- Definition varies by **asset class**

### Equities: Bought with Cash or on Margin

**Dividend yield, %**
- Expected dividend yield per year during holding period
- Or for simplicity: historic dividend ÷ current price

**Funding cost, %**
- Either: interest you could have received on cash if not invested
- Or: if borrowing on margin, your cost of funding

**Net expected return, %**
- Dividend yield minus funding cost

**Net expected return in price units**
- Net expected return % multiplied by current price

### Equities: Contracts for Difference (CFD)

**Dividend yield, %**
- Expected dividend yield per year during holding period
- Or for simplicity: historic dividend ÷ current price

**Funding cost, %**
- Average of interest you pay to fund long position and what you receive on short positions

**Net expected return, %**
- Dividend yield minus funding cost

**Net expected return in price units**
- Net expected return % multiplied by current price

### Foreign Exchange: Cash

**Interest, %**
- Interest you get in the foreign currency

**Funding cost, %**
- Interest you pay to borrow domestic currency

**Net expected return, %**
- Interest minus funding cost

**Net expected return in price units**
- Net expected return % multiplied by current price

### Spread Bet (e.g. on FX or Equities)

**Spread bet level**
- Mid-price level of spread bet
- Assumes financing cost priced into relationship between spot and spread bet price

**Spot level**
- Level of spot price of relevant instrument at same time

**Net expected return over bet period**
- Spot level minus spread bet level

**Time to maturity**
- Time to expiry of bet, in years
- Quarterly three-month bet would be 0.25

**Net expected return in price units**
- Net expected return over bet period ÷ time to maturity

### Futures: If Not Trading Nearest Contract (Preferred)

**Current contract price**
- Price of contract you are trading

**Nearer contract price**
- Price of next closest contract
- Example: trading June 2017 Eurodollar, nearer would be March 2017

**Price differential**
- Current contract price minus nearer contract price

**Distance between contracts**
- Time in years between the two contracts
- Adjacent quarterly expires: 0.25
- Adjacent monthly: 0.083

**Net expected return in price units**
- Annualize price differential by dividing by distance between contracts

> If you are already trading the nearest contract you obviously can't use this method. Instead there is an approximation below, which assumes you get the same amount of expected return for the first two available contracts.

### Futures: If Trading Nearest Contract (Approximation)

**Current contract price**
- Price of contract you are trading

**Next contract price**
- Price of contract with next expiry
- Example: June 2017 Treasury bonds → September 2017

**Price differential**
- Next contract price minus current contract price

**Distance between contracts**
- Time in years between the two contracts
- Adjacent quarterly expires: 0.25
- Adjacent monthly: 0.083

**Net expected return in price units**
- Annualize price differential by dividing by distance between contracts

### Forecast Calculation

**Net expected return in price units**
- From relevant information above
- Note: this is annualized measure

**Standard deviation of returns**
- Standard deviation of returns in price points (not percentage)
- Volatility in price points equals percentage point volatility (**price volatility** as defined in chapter 10, 'Position sizing', page 155) multiplied by current price

**Annualized standard deviation of returns**
- Multiply standard deviation by 'square root of time' to annualize
- Assuming 256 business days per year: multiply by 16

**Raw carry: Volatility standardised expected return**
- Net expected return in price units ÷ annualized standard deviation of returns
- As noted in chapter 7, forecasts should be adjusted for return standard deviation

**Forecast scalar**
- Forecast scalar is 30
- Multiplier explanation in appendix below

**Forecast**
- Forecast scalar × raw carry

**Capped forecast**
- Forecast with values outside range -20, +20 capped

### Which Forecast Scalar to Use
- Raw carry measure is effectively annualized **Sharpe ratio (SR)**
- Expected return ÷ standard deviation
- Author used technique in Appendix D with data from large markets across different **asset classes**
- Gives forecast scalar around 30

### What is the Turnover of Carry
- Hard to generalize about **turnover** (round trips per year)
- Depends on asset class and update frequency
- Suggest checking forecast weekly to avoid spurious noise
- If weekly updates, reasonable to use rule of thumb value of 10 for carry rule turnover

## Appendix C: Portfolio Optimisation

### More Details on Bootstrapping

#### Bootstrapping 101
- Assumes returns already **volatility normalised** with same expected standard deviation
- Steps:
  1. Choose random subset of past returns (from all history or recent period depending on expanding/rolling window)
  2. Calculate correlation and average returns from that subset
  3. Run normal optimisation using correlation and mean returns of subset
  4. Record resulting instrument weights
  5. Repeat step 1 multiple times
  6. For each asset, take all instrument weights from past optimisations and average them out

#### How Should You Select Return Periods
- In simple example (chapter 4), drew individual daily returns at random
- Example: 30 August 2002 could be followed by 1 February 2000
- Makes life easier, usually reasonable approximation
- But sometimes arbitrary selection doesn't make sense
- Poor returns in one asset might be followed by good returns in another
- Time series correlation lost unless adjacent days kept together
- Solution: do **'block' bootstrapping**
- Each subset consists of appropriate number of **consecutive** returns
- Only randomness is choice of starting date
- Block length needs to be long enough to capture time dependence

#### How Long Should Each Period Be
- Month of daily returns, year, or longer?
- Shorter periods: more extreme optimisation, wider distributions, larger confidence intervals
- Longer periods: more sensible results, but doesn't mean average distribution better
- Academic research examined this in depth
- Author's analysis: small benefit (0.05 **Sharpe ratio** improvement) from using **multiple years** versus only a month
- Assumes couple decades' worth of data in total
- **Rule of thumb: use samples equal to 10% of history available**
- Example: 30 years of data → use three year-long samples for each optimisation

#### How Many Times to Repeat
- More iterations always better but with decreasing benefits
- Almost no value doing 200 vs 100 iterations unless block size very small relative to history

### Does Bootstrapping Work
- Academic research focused on this extensively
- Author's view: bootstrapping definitely superior to **single period optimisation** and **equal weights**
- Own research with artificial data: single period performs slightly better when lots of structure
- Underlying **Sharpe ratio (SR)** and **correlations** quite different
- Obviously equal weights better when underlying SR and correlations very similar
- Never know in advance which situation applies
- Overall bootstrapping most consistent method with less variability across different data sets
- Random generated data isn't as noisy as real data
- Studies probably understate benefits of bootstrapping

> Personally I also find bootstrapping to be as good or better than other, relatively complex, methods.

### Rule of Thumb Correlations
- Following are approximate, use with caution
- **Correlations vary considerably over time**, can be much higher or lower
- First: correlation of instrument price returns across different 'super' **asset classes**
- 'Volatility' refers to positions in **equity volatility indices** (holding long position in VIX or V2TX futures)
- To avoid showing negative correlations, displayed as if you had short position (i.e. you want volatility to fall)

**Table 50: Correlations of Instrument Returns Across Super-Asset Classes**

|            | Bonds | Equities | FX  | Commodities | Volatility |
|------------|-------|----------|-----|-------------|------------|
| Rates      | 1     |          |     |             |            |
| Equities   | 0.1   | 1        |     |             |            |
| FX         | 0.1   | 0.1      | 1   |             |            |
| Commodities| 0.1   | 0.1      | 0.25| 1           |            |
| Volatility | 0.1   | 0.6      | 0.2 | 0.1         | 1          |

